## 2. Research Question & Hypothesis

### 2.1 Research Question
**"Can transformer-based models (DistilBERT) achieve significantly higher accuracy than traditional machine learning approaches (TF-IDF + Logistic Regression) for binary sentiment classification of IMDB movie reviews?"**

### 2.2 Hypotheses (Testable, Falsifiable, Reproducible)

**H1 (Primary):** A fine-tuned DistilBERT model will achieve F1-score ≥ 0.90 on the IMDB test set.

**H2 (Comparative):** DistilBERT will outperform TF-IDF + Logistic Regression baseline by at least 5% in F1-score.

**H3 (Feature Engineering):** Including metadata features (word count, punctuation, sentiment word counts) will improve traditional ML model performance by at least 2%.

**H4 (Model Complexity):** LSTM models will achieve F1-score between baseline and DistilBERT, demonstrating the value of transformer architecture.

**Null Hypothesis (H0):** There is no statistically significant difference (p > 0.05) between transformer models and traditional ML approaches for this task.

### 2.3 Why This is Testable
- Clear metric: F1-score (macro average)
- Defined threshold: 0.90 F1-score
- Comparative baseline: TF-IDF + Logistic Regression
- Statistical testing: McNemar's test, paired t-test with cross-validation

### 2.4 Why This is Falsifiable
- If DistilBERT achieves F1 < 0.90, H1 is rejected
- If improvement over baseline < 5%, H2 is rejected
- Experimental results can prove hypotheses wrong

### 2.5 Why This is Reproducible
- Public dataset: [IMDB 50K Dataset on Kaggle](https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/lakshmi25npathi/imdb-dataset-of-50k-movie-reviews)
- Fixed random seeds (random_state=42)
- Fixed train/val/test split (70/15/15)
- All code in GitHub with requirements.txt
- Documented preprocessing steps
- Model hyperparameters specified

